    "summary": "Hagar Qim is a megalithic temple complex on the southern cliffs of Malta, constructed during the Maltese Temple Period approximately 3600–3200 BCE. It belongs to the [[event:1666|Maltese Temple Period]] and stands as one of the best-preserved examples of a tradition unique to the Maltese archipelago. The complex features the largest stones used in any Maltese temple, with one orthostatic block weighing an estimated six tons and measuring over five meters in length.\n\nThe temple's orientation aligns with the summer solstice sunrise, and carved spiral decorations on internal altar stones suggest astronomical and ritual significance. Excavations at Hagar Qim have yielded figurines, animal bones, and ash deposits interpreted as evidence of animal sacrifice and feasting rituals. The site sits close to the Mnajdra temples on the same clifftop, forming a ceremonial complex that served prehistoric communities across Malta and Gozo.",
